segments.text: Mike Winand that was on the microphone and describing how they were going to pass a certain certain law to make such and such legal and this and that and it was being broadcast to spectators and everybody.

That was fun and of course Mardi Gras if you as an RV is an interesting it's the wildest time it's it's not carnival and all that mess and staying on aircraft carrier but it was the Mardi Gras Day parade and fighting the drunks in New Orleans and it was the physical hand-to-hand combat of getting through the streets of New Orleans we had one drunk that fell into our ranks hit slid off one guy turned around and we were told to hit them and get them out of our ranks

And I didn't know what else to do, and this guy was kind of staggering and swinging at another guy, and so I hit him over the head with my rifle, and he just fell to the ground, and our platoon just marched right over him.
And I guess he's still there.
I don't know what happened to him.
Now, how did you all get to Austin and to New Orleans?
Personal car.
You just got there, however.
Show up, be there, here's where we are.
And you were expected to pay the, you, the RVs were to pay the car expense.
Absolutely.
You're on your own.
Where did you spend the night?
We stayed on the aircraft carrier Lexington, which was docked at Bienville Street Wharf.
And we got there, and this is where they put the Citadel and VPI and all these little groups.
We got to look, and they had all this huge carrier bay
on the first level with all these cots and the lights are on 24 hours.
Wait a minute, this isn't a good deal.
So we poked around the ship until we found the end of the ship where the anchor comes out was a small room that would accommodate probably 40 or 50 cots and a lot quieter and dark.
And outside of losing one kid from the Citadel that fell out the anchor hole when he was throwing up, that was our place.
And so we had our own place, and we found a separate head that we could shower and bathe in.
Aggies tend to just find things and make them work, and it worked a whole lot better.
What did you and your buddies think about those Citadel and VMI?
Oh, we visited with them, and there's always a lot of competition, whatever.
We all go through a lot of the same things.
Our impression was A&M's still a better place.
We got more out of it.
I spent a week with the Student Council on Urban Affairs or whatever, the SCONA counterpart at the Air Force Academy.
And I'd had a cousin that was wing commander at the Air Force Academy in 69.
And he'd spent a week with me at A&M.
And he said, there's no comparison.
What you have at A&M, we lost 20 years ago.
You know, the hazing and things, the good bull at A&M, this didn't happen in service academies.
They don't anymore because under the eye of Congress and
any complaint to somebody's mommy, and you've got a congressional investigation.
Meanwhile, back in the vet school, what were some very meaningful experiences you now realize in those three years as a vet student?
Three full years.
A lot of intense academics, going to school with people that all are pretty well focused on what they want to do.
And, of course, a lot of them married, some with kids.
This was a new experience for me.
And developing, again, another set of wonderful friendships that continue to this day, like Pete and Sue Baden and others.
You start, you find out, especially when you get into your clinical rotations, that a number of the veterinarians there have never been in private practice.
Not that private practice is everything, but that's the majority of students are going to go.
And so you tend to couch a lot of what you learn with, well, that may or may not be the way it really is on the outside.
Most of the classes were probably the hardest class was for our class in that nine trimesters was Dr. Worsig's toxicology class.
And we had two classmates that were right on the brink of failing.
And so we were kind of,
really up in arms about that as any class would be.
And there were a lot of complaints to the dean and back and forth and a lot of low grades.
And it was a real tense time.
And we showed up for the class that it was all looks like everything was going to come down.
And Dr. Worsig gets behind the podium and bends down and disappears for a minute and comes back up with a catcher's mask

and a chest protector on and he said okay you sons of bitches I'm ready for you and that kind of broke the ice because after that we realized he is human and after that we were okay and the guys didn't fail and we all got out of there and everything was fine but that was uh it took some guts on his part to do that and did uh
Did those students that were in danger before that time, did they deserve to pass?
Probably not.
And those two that had trouble, neither one of them were practicing today.
No, so I can now catch that with nearly 27 years of experience.
Clinically, they just weren't cut out for practicing.
Were there any routines in the preparation years in vet school, were there any routines that at that time you all thought might be a little bit out of date?
No, I'm not.
We didn't have a lot to gauge it by.
Been a huge technology boost in our profession as there is in all the health professions.
I think a few things we felt there were other procedures we were aware of that weren't being performed at the vet school at the time, especially in large animal medicine.
At that time, they had a much older large animal clinical staff that have since all gone on and
Many have passed away.
Many of them came to the school because of the drought of the 50s.
And that teaching was antiquated and behind.
And we had no problems with the small animal sector, but some armed open conflict with some of the large animal clinicians.
But that was probably the only place.
Everything else, we didn't have anything to compare it to.
Did you have anyone that you gradually developed a relationship with to be a kind of an advisor?
Probably a couple people that I could visit with, but again, since I was going into the Air Force, I was so shot in the rear with importance that I didn't spend a lot of time being mentored.
We were really, this is one of the evils of the trimester system, it was too intense and too fast, and that's why they quit it, because there was a lot of burnout on both sides of the fence.
What did you think you were gonna do after the Air Force?

I thought, you know, there was always private practice, but didn't know, and I thought at one time I might be interested in a zoo or an exotic type practice working for one of the major zoological gardens, something like that.
That was before I graduated, after I'm in the service for a while.
In fact, I even had a job with the United Nations if I decided to stay in North Africa.
realizing you want to do that and i really got interested in making a living in very medicine got interested in common product clinical practice the
As far as you knew, what was your Air Force duty going to be?
As far as you knew before you got into it.
I knew because I knew where I was going to go, say, six months before.
I'd been told if I got an early commissioning program, Archie Flowers said, no problem, you'll get your choice of assignments because you're signing up three years early.
And I said, great.
I want to go to Europe.
And they said, gee, sorry, but there's nothing open in Europe.
But if you volunteer to go to Southeast Asia, then
You know, you can get your choice in a year.
But y'all promised.
Well, it doesn't work quite that way.
So I end up volunteering, and I go to Southeast Asia.
And then after I'm there, the same thing.
Well, yeah, but there's nothing open.
Well, I got on a true red phone in the SAC, Advanced Echelon Targeting Headquarters, down in the bunker.
at NKP Thailand and called and talked to a veterinarian at a Navy base in North Africa named Jim Jordan, a Kansas State graduate.
And he said, this is the greatest place in the world.
If you like to travel, if you like the outdoors, if you want to see the world, the Navy doesn't know what we do.
Come on over.
A&M prepared me tremendously well to deal with the U.S. military.
It was like taking candy from a baby.
And we, three years in the service, I averaged traveling over 90 days a year around the world.
All right.
Were you really working in public health?
No.
I was doing, unlike most veterinarians, I did not have hardly any public health responsibility.
I did clinical practice.
So I did guard dogs.

ran a pet clinic in Morocco, guard dogs both in Southeast Asia and Morocco, Southeast Asia, medical civic action, working with pigs and people and water buffalos in the villages, doing a lot of human medicine, both on GIs and Orientals, and wonderful training.
No veterinarians, nobody to mentor me.
I was by myself, and I delivered some babies.
Never done it before.
They say, you American doctor.
I said, wrong kind of doctor.
Didn't care.
So I got a baptism of fire of a different kind.
It was very maturing.
Let's see.
Let's come back to the campus.
You were in vet school when Mr.
Rudder dies.
Right.
What did, how did you and your buddies hear about it?
What did you all think?
It was announced at Morning Chow, all of our announcements, and I didn't know him, but I knew a lot about him.
I'd seen him, but, you know, seen his old bulldog wandering the campus and stuff, but, you know, you... What image did he have with you and your friends?
Oh, about like John Wayne, I guess.
And a lot of respect because, and I keep going back to this, but this is 1968, 1969.
It was a tough time in America because of the Vietnam War.
And we felt, we're in the Corps of Cadets, you know, we're different than the rest of the college campuses for many reasons.
And Earl Rutter never caved, never changed.
Quality was there, he was a neat guy, and yeah, it was, we didn't know him personally, but he was our leader.
And did you go to the memorial service?
I did, went through the rotunda there.
I was not, the RVs were the honor guard there, and I was a sophomore, was not a Ross volunteer at the time, but I remember seeing Lyndon Johnson.
Politically, I didn't care for him at all, but I thought, you know, it's a pretty big,
Must have been a big man if you've got the President of the United States coming to visit.
Yeah, that's right.
He was President.
He was President at the time.
And all the others.
This is not part of the interview to record.
Guess how old Earl Rudder was when he died?
I have absolutely no idea.
One month short of his 60th birthday, and since he was a reserve officer,
he did not qualify for veterans benefits.
And even Olin Teague, his classmate, who was chairman of the House Veterans Affairs Committee, could not get an exception made for him.
Amazing.
You see, I'll be 70 next month.
60 is fairly young, I think.
Oh, yeah.
But by today's standards, he, and so Mrs. Rutter doesn't get
I saw her at Rick Perry's swearing-in.
Don't know her.
She was in the company of two cadets and a pleasant lady.
That's a shame.
It really is.
That's a travesty.
Oh, yes.
He did a splendid job.
All right.
Did you and your buddies, did you all have any image of Jack Williams when he becomes the president in the fall of 1970?
Wasn't the same kind of guy.
Wasn't cut from the same bolt.
I don't really know somebody.
I just remember calling him Smiling Jack.
He was president, I guess for, I can't remember how many years.
Six.
Six years.
Okay, about right.
And my parents were Aggie Parents of the Year.
around 76, 77, somewhere in there, but I believe he was still here.
Yeah, because he becomes the system chancellor in 77.
Okay.
And Jarvis Miller becomes the president.
He was still there because my folks were here.
They met you.
I'm sure you don't remember Dorothy Claytor, but we met at a little social as part of their weekend, parents' weekend.
I was just gotten out of the service, was in practice in Pleasanton, and littlest brother Dan was probably junior in the Corps at the time, and
We had all sent our letters in, and with four boys in the Corps, mom and dad were Aggie Parents of the Year, so kind of a neat deal.
See, I tell people, only Earl Rudder could have made the changes he made.
I don't think anybody else is strong enough, to be honest.
I understand enough about politics and about leadership that it took somebody that had an ironclad will and the intestinal fortitude to stand up and say, this is how we're going to do it, boys.
Then he lays the foundation, strong and firm.
Then Jack Williams academically builds on it.
And Rutter couldn't have done what Williams did, but vice versa.
No, and I don't think any one man could ever have done it all.
There's no way.
But the school, they don't work that way.
And look at this place today.
I walked around here seeing new things, and some things don't change, but a lot of things do.
Oh, yes.
Back in your student days, you were in the Corps and all that.
Tell me about when you got that ring.
I remember going by, I believe it was the Koch Building.
I believe that's where you paid your money, and I don't... Do you remember what it cost?
I think it was $180, but I don't... That figure, that may be wrong.
It's way less than what kids pay for.
I don't know what they cost today.
Do you know what they... $300 or $400, I don't know.
And I remember putting it on and thinking...
Gee, I just got here.
And now, you know, I'm a senior.
And this ring has literally been around the world.
I was telling Kyle I was in a bar at the Oberoi Hilton Hotel in New Delhi, India in 1975.
And two drinks show up, extra visit with a guy.
And I said, no, we didn't order these.
And he said, no, that gentleman did over there.
And a guy does like this and gets up and walks over and
Jack's somebody, class of 54.
The guy says, how do you know each other?
He said, we're brothers.
And that was it.
We didn't even visit.
Just, yeah, you know.
And he was over on some railway construction deal and ran a deal, but just saw the ring.
That's all it took.
Have you ever lost it?
Left it in the bathroom in Vietnam, and the waiter brought it out to me.
Can you imagine?
And I'm one of the few veterinarians who haven't lost it in a cow.
It has gone through linen service in San Antonio in the khaki pants we wear at the clinic, and they found it for me at Unifirst, and they returned it.
And that's been it.
I'm very careful.
I hope I don't ever do it.
When I interviewed...

When I interviewed President Bowen, I asked him, and he said that when he was a vet student at Caltech, I believe it was, I mean a graduate student at Caltech, he's in Europe on a summer research trip, and he and two German buddies are on the train going from Vienna to Venice.
And as they're going over the Alps, this lady is reading a newspaper and turns down and said, are you from Texas A&M?
Well, yes, ma'am.
How did you know?
Well, I saw your ring.
And he introduced himself.
And she said, well, my name is Zachary.
My husband, HB Zachary, is one of the biggest construction.
And he was much impressed.
Was there a camaraderie built in the vet school that was at all similar to the camaraderie built in the Corps?
No.
No.
Although I have friends in vet school, and it was a fairly close class and fun, it's just not the same.
It's a totally different experience.
Totally different.

But there's enough intensity in vet school that it does bring you together, and it's genuinely good to see my practicing colleagues, and some I've stayed very close to, but it's not the same as the Corps.
Were there some events
as a part of the three years in vet school that are important traditions, important binders?
They would have an annual fish fry with, I think, seniors and faculty.
And then they would have a get together, can't remember what it was, a barbecue or something, again, with like freshman students.

A few things like that, that the senior fish fry, I got in a fight with David Hanselka, one of the clinicians, and he ended up biting a chunk out of my elbow, and I'm not a fighter, but it was just one of those, that was during our burnout stage with the large animal practitioners.
Outside of a few get-togethers like that, you had your veterinary wives put together some socials.
Most of those failed miserably.
Were you married by then?
No, no, I was single.
I married when I was 30, so I was already about long since been out of school.
But I was well treated by so many folks.
They had an open door to many of us vet students.
I look back on a lot of those vet wives and
living with no money and working hard and husband going to school.
I admire him.
Where did you live after you finished those four undergraduate years or four core years?
Well, I had the, of course, part of that was in vet school.
So in the summertime, I was at Schumacher Hall and then back for my senior year in the core.
But I'm still in vet school.
And then when I got out of the core, we lived out until I finished vet school out
On Travis Whedon's country, we used to have the old dairy and have some rent houses.
Travis and Joyce Whedon, which were just wonderful people.
And they fed us three or four nights out of the week.
They made no money off of our rent.
Wonderful people.
And that's where I lived out in the country until I got out of vet school.
Then immediately went on active duty and was overseas basically continually for a little over three and a half years.
And then ended up in Pleasanton in 1976.
Alright, so you, back to traditions for a second.
You go through, at the end of your third year, you go through final review and become, in one way, a senior in the Corps.
Right.
Tell me about what it was like to put on those senior boots.
That was, and that's another real special time.
Obviously, you've talked to others, but you put them on for the first time.
I got my boots made at Economy Boot and Shoe in San Antonio, Texas.
Went down, a group of us went down, got them ordered, and they were a lot cheaper than Hollick's, and that has no bearing on anything, but it was a trip to San Antonio as juniors.
We got measured, got them made.
put them on for the first time.
You beg, borrow, and steal pants and you buy old, your pants from other upperclassmen.
Never buy anything new if you can avoid it.
How much did your boots cost?
Mine were, at that time I believe, were $90.
And now was this your money or mother and dad's money?
This was mine that I'd saved and got ready to spend it and got a check in the mail from my dad for the boots and the spurs.
And he said, I didn't go to A&M, but I will, for everyone of y'all to become seniors in the Corps, I will buy your boots, which I appreciated very much.
Put those boots on for the first time, and I remember Bob Shepard was

had been a roommate and my outfit gave me a room by myself from my junior year on because I was the only one in vet school and back then that was a big deal to have a room by yourself and I probably didn't need it but it was appreciated but Bob had been one of my sophomore roommates he was from Hillsboro and he wanted to be my he said do you have an executive officer and I said no you're it and
In fact, I saw Bob at Rick Perry's swearing in also.
Good friend.
Bob is a pilot for American Airlines.
Putting on those boots for the first time and then walking back, there is not a bigger feeling in the world.
You talk about being shot in the rear with importance because you're finally there.
And you're clunking with those boots and you're feeling pretty good.
And it's a neat deal.
Did family come to find a review?
They did.
They did.
My folks made every...
to my knowledge, every final review that I was in, but for certain that's the only one I remember was that one and then of course the next year also, the true final review.
All right, now that true final review as you phrased it, did you go through commencement then?
Yes, I did.
I got a degree in veterinary science.
That was just a manufactured degree because you've done the hours.
It's worthless, but did it and graduated.
I want to graduate in uniform, not in a cap and gown.
And that was good to graduate with my class.
Did you and your buddies do any celebrating that night?
No, I don't think so.
I think I did my college.
In fact, I know my folks were here and I had
a set of almost surrogate parents that I'd met through my Colorado days in the summer, Michael and Nancy Kangurga from Henderson, Texas, both of them University of Texas graduates.
I'm the first.
They knew Jim Anderson well, but I'm the first Aggie in the Corps that they'd known well.
They had a son that was a year younger than me that was at SMU.
And they came down to my graduation.
And looking back on it, I really appreciate it.
They didn't need to do that.
But they were in many ways like a second set of parents, because Henderson was a good bit closer to Midland.
And as a vet student and as a senior in the Corps, I could retreat to Henderson sometimes.
Now, your undergraduate degree was in G. Raleigh.
Where was that veterinary commencement?
Was it over there also?
For some reason, I think it was.
Well, in fact, I know it was.
Yes, it was.
And I guess we graduated in August, but there were others graduating at that time.
But it was at G. Raleigh also.
How are you holding up, Kyle?
You can drift out if you need to.
We're about done.
All right.
I don't have too much more.
This is another editor's note.

Sometime about in the early 70s, as dean of faculties, I was in President Jack Williams' office one day, and he tossed two letters at me, each written by the mother of a student who was scheduled to graduate that summer.
A&M was not having summer graduations at that time, and these ladies were saying it wasn't
that their sons had to wait until December to graduate.
And both of them had a job that was going to take them far away.
And they asked the question, why doesn't A&M have a summer commencement?
And he said, what do you think?
And we both agreed that they asked a very good question.
Let's try it.
And we both wondered, would anybody show up?
And of course, summer commencement now is as well attended per person as any other.
I'm sure it is.
Sure.
And nobody.
And that was in 1970?
That was in 71, I think.
It was pretty early.
Because my commencement was in August of 73, and looking back on it, yeah, there had to have been, there was other people besides veterinarians there, that's for sure.
And did you look carefully at the tube, at what was in your tube, to be sure the diploma was there?
I'm sure I did.
I don't recall.
But you kind of, boy, I hope this thing's not empty.
As you look back on your veterinary preparation, is there any change you now, if you had been in charge then, based on experience, any change in the curriculum?
Curriculum I probably wouldn't change.
I would probably specifically add some practice management courses.
Dennis McKernan at LSU is big on this.
However, you can lead a horse to water, but you can't make him drink.
Until the financial pistol is at your head, you will not pay attention.
So for the practitioner in me, I would say that.
But no.
I would probably give even more attention to internal medicine and surgery.
Again, as a practitioner, because that's what I do.
But for where we were in 1973, we were well educated.
And I didn't realize this until I started dealing with physicians in Southeast Asia and then in North Africa, that I'd gotten a darn good education.
I would have, and I'm glad they have gone to a four-year program instead of the trimester.
It was hard on everybody.
There was no time to relax, was there?
No, and there was no time to make any money.
And the financial onus, these veterinary students are getting out owing, even with time off, they're owing an average of $44,000 a year, and that's just the average.
All right, again looking back, to what degree
faculty members, advisors, would you most want to express your gratitude for what they did during those years?
Who did the best job and how did they do it?
Oh, I think everybody has favorite professors.
Dr. Mike Herron, who's recently retired as an orthopedist, was a good clinical instructor.
Again, I mentioned Mike Tatum and Gerald Bratton.
What did they do that made the most sense?
They cared about their students.
And this is the one common thread.

you know as an aside you can strike this from memory but you're still probably my most memorable professor from undergraduate days because well because you pushed me and and I learned in your class and I learned about myself
because I don't remember the names of my other professors.
They were there and they were fine, but I don't remember them.
So you focus on, and it's the people that you've got something in return.
You didn't just regurgitate, but you were pushed, you were exhorted, you were cajoled, you were encouraged, and you were counseled.
Did anybody ever call you in and sort of kick your rear and say, hey, you can do this better and I'll get with it?
Not to my knowledge.
Gee, Wayne Stark did that in the MSC occasionally with student leaders.
He did some, and I knew Wayne Stark, but I didn't, I can't think of any.
I can sure remember a seventh grade teacher, Doris Watson, did that to me one day, and I'll never forget that.
In vet school, as you look back, do you think you did about as well as you could have done?
Did you work about as hard as you could have?
No.
No, I could have worked a whole lot harder, but I was in vet school,

It was obvious I wasn't going to get, I wasn't going to flunk out and I wasn't going to leave and I was young and single and although, you know, A&M wasn't the cultural mecca of the world, it was all I had and I had the core.
So I had, I had a lot of other stuff to do besides go to vet school.
So I balanced, but I did enough to get by and did what I was interested in, but looking back on it, probably a little immature.
If I was older, I probably would have taken more advantage of it.
Let's see, one of the things that we should have asked about earlier, when you were an undergraduate, were you aware of the existence of secret fraternities?
Now, Class of 72, I'm not, you know, I mean, we had our, a group of aardvarks as freshmen, as crowns, as materials.
Wasn't aware of any, and may have been some, but there weren't any in the Corps that I'm aware of, and there weren't any others.
We didn't have civilian students.
I'm not sure, an interesting question.
What creates Aggie spirit?
What creates the devotion and feeling?
Bonding with other people.
Respect and loyalty for your fellow man.
What encourages that bonding?
An environment where
By yourself you can't stand, but with your buddies you can.
Coming together is one.
Are there some events that are important?
Your freshman year in the Corps of Cadets, and this is, I don't want to hurt anybody's feelings, it's very difficult to feel a deep Aggie bonding without being in the Corps.
I can't relate to it because I was never a civilian student as an undergraduate, but things like bonfire, like fetal pigs in the mess hall, or like mess hall any night of the week,
you get a certain level of love, respect, and discipline from a family.
And this is why gang members, this is what they think they're getting out of their gangs on the streets.
I deal with gang members in Bible studies.
The Corps of Cadets is a different kind of gang, but love, respect, and discipline in its own way.
That's the central part of the Aggie spirit.
Does bonfire yell practice?
Every one of them.
Every one of them add to the final sum, to the quotient.
And if you take bonfire away, you need to replace it with something else as meaningful.
It's more than cutting down logs and burning them.
It's about bonding together.
Stealing foot lockers is not about theft, but it's about bonding together.
